definition.value: A methyl-branched fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any 2-methyl fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.

A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-aspartic acid at the amino group or either of the carboxy groups, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-aspartic acid by a heteroatom.

A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-glutamic acid at the amino group or either of the carboxy groups, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-glutamic acid by a heteroatom.
Any metabolite (endogenous or exogenous) found in human urine samples.
A sialodiaosylceramide that is an alpha-N-acetylneuraminosyl-(2->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl-N-acylsphingosine in which the acyl group on nitrogen is (15Z)-tetracos-15-enoyl.

A glycotetraosylceramide in which a linear beta-D-GalNAc-(1->3)-alpha-D-Gal-(1->-4)-beta-D-Gal-(1->4)-beta-D-Glc tetrasaccharide unit is linked glycosidically to a (3R,4E)-3-hydroxy-2-(pentacosanoylamino)octadec-4-en-1-yl ceramide group.
A non-proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of D-proline at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of D-proline by a heteroatom.
A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-proline at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-proline  by a heteroatom.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any 3-hydroxy fatty acid.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any (omega-1)-hydroxy fatty acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A glycotriaosylceramide having alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl as the glycotriaosyl component attached to the Cer(d18:1/18:0).
Any member of the class of  indoles carrying at least one hydroxy group.
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in algae including unicellular organisms like chlorella and diatoms to multicellular organisms like giant kelps and brown algae.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion that is the conjugate base of 2-aminoadipic acid.
A carbocyclic fatty acid composed of heptanoic acid having a (1S,2S)-2-octylcyclopentyl substituent at position 7.
Any cosmetic used to lighten the colour of skin by reducing the concentration of melanin.
Any metabolite (endogenous or exogenous) found in human blood serum samples.
A D-alpha-amino acid zwitterion resulting from a transfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group of D-alloisoleucine; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion resulting from a transfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group of L-alloisoleucine; major species at pH 7.3.
Any substance that inhibits the action of glycine transporters.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the acyl group specified is dodecenoyl.
Any mammalian metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in rat (Rattus norvegicus).
Any antifungal agent used to prevent or treat fungal infections in humans or animals.
A hydroxy-amino acid in which the amino acid specified is proline. A "closed" class.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the  conjugate base of alpha-aminobutyric acid.
An anionic ganglioside in which the oligosaccharide portion is composed of a disaccharide, to which one sialic acid residue is attached.

A glycotetraosylceramide having N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->3)-alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl  component attached to the primary hydroxy function of a ceramide with undefined sphingoid base.
Any metal which causes the onset of an allergic reaction.
Any drug which causes the onset of an allergic reaction.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-methylsuccinic acid
An EC 6.4.1.* (carboxylase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of pyruvate carboxylase (EC 6.4.1.1).
A drug that acts as an antagonist, agonist, reverse agonist, or in some other fashion when interacting with cellular receptors.
Any peptide zwitterion comprising two amino acid residues. Major structure at pH 7.3.
A carboxylic acic anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any aromatic carboxylic acid. Major species at pH 7.3.
A dicarboxylic acid that is butanedioic acid substituted at position 2 by a methyl group.
A 2-methylbutanedioic acid in which the methyl group at position 2 has S-configuration.
A 2-methylbutanedioic acid in which the methyl group at position 2 has R-configuration.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,6-dicarboxy derivative of hexane.

value.value: A material entity of anatomical origin (part of or deriving from an organism) that has as its parts a maximally connected cell compartment surrounded by a plasma membrane.

definition.value: The definition of cell is intended to represent all cells, and thus a cell is defined as a material entity and not an anatomical structure, which implies that it is part of an organism (or the entirety of one).

value.value: Any fibroblast that is derived from the neural crest.
Any sensory receptor cell that is a(n) neuron and is capable of some detection of stimulus involved in sensory perception.
A cell found in the embryo before the formation of all the gem layers is complete.

Cell that is part of the migratory cranial neural crest population. Migratory cranial neural crest cells develop from premigratory cranial neural crest cells and have undergone epithelial to mesenchymal transition and delamination.

Cell that is part of the migratory trunk neural crest population. Migratory trunk neural crest cells develop from premigratory trunk neural crest cells and have undergone epithelial to mesenchymal transition and delamination.
A stem cell that is the precursor of gametes.
A germ cell that supports male gamete production. In some species, non-germ cells known as Sertoli cells also play a role in spermatogenesis.
A male germ cell that develops from spermatogonia. The euploid primary spermatocytes undergo meiosis and give rise to the haploid secondary spermatocytes which in turn give rise to spermatids.
A male germ cell that develops from the haploid secondary spermatocytes. Without further division, spermatids undergo structural changes and give rise to spermatozoa.
A mature male germ cell that develops from a spermatid.
